# Git Workflow

## Commit Signing Requirements

All commits must include:
- **Signed-off-by** (`-s`): DCO signoff line in commit message
- **GPG signature** (`-S`): Cryptographic signature

Always use `git commit -s -S` when creating commits.

## Commit Message Conventions

Follow [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) format for upstream contributions:

```
<type>: <description> (#PR)

<optional body>

Signed-off-by: Your Name <email@example.com>
```

### Type Prefixes

| Prefix | Usage |
|--------|-------|
| `feat:` | New features |
| `fix:` | Bug fixes |
| `chore:` | Maintenance, dependency updates |
| `ci:` | CI/CD changes |
| `docs:` | Documentation |

### Optional Scope

Include scope in parentheses when helpful: `fix(llmisvc): description`

### Examples

```
feat: Add pathTemplate configuration for inference service routing (#4817)

Signed-off-by: Your Name <email@example.com>
```

```
fix: clear stale router and scheduler conditions on config changes (#4876)

Signed-off-by: Your Name <email@example.com>
```

### CVE References

For security fixes, reference the CVE directly in the subject:
```
CVE-2024-43598: Update lightgbm version to 4.6.0 (#4799)
```

### Changing the Base Branch In-Place

If you started on the wrong base (e.g., ODH instead of upstream), rebase in-place:

```bash
# Stash uncommitted changes
git stash -u -m "WIP changes"

# Reset to the correct base
git fetch upstream
git reset --hard upstream/master

# Apply stashed changes
git stash pop
```